@Niall Ó Cofaigh: The agreement in 2017 to include a backstop only comes into legal effect if May’s deal is accepted by the British parliament.
Under Article 50 the UK leaves the EU by default on the 29th of March 2018, if the deal is accepted then both parties namely the UK and EU have a further 2 years to work out the many details of their future relationship within legal frameworks, trade deals and many unforseen consequences of brexit etc.
The purpose of the backstop is, if they can’t actually workout the details during that next 2 year period as seems increasingly likely, then the backstop would come into effect, preventing the hard border indefinitely, until such time as a further agreement that was acceptable by all parties namely the UK and EU was adopted.

